# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Need the sizes of all the subtrees (subordinate as well as above one) to calculate each node's score.

2. Calculate sizes of left & right subordinate subtree as we run the dfs function for the current node.

3. Now to get the size of above tree, we simply can deduct the `sum of sizes of subordinate tree + 1 (current node)` from the total number of nodes(N).
Therefore, `size of above subtree = N - sum - 1`.

4. Calculate score and store it in `allScores` array while keeping track of `maxScore`.Return count of `maxScore` in `allScores`.

---


# Complexity
- Time complexity: **O(n)** - *dfs, traversing parent, allScores array*
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: **O(n)** - *tree adjajency list, allScores array*
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

---


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int N;
    long maxScore = 0;
    vector<long> allScores;

    long dfs(int node,vector<vector<int>>& tree){

        long score = 1;
        long sum = 0;
        for(int v:tree[node]){

            long res = dfs(v,tree);
            sum += res;
            score *= res;
        }
        sum++; // added current
        score *= (N-sum>0) ? N-sum : 1; // to check that score doesn't gets multiplied by 0 for root node
        maxScore = max(maxScore,score);
        allScores.push_back(score);

        return sum;
    }
    int countHighestScoreNodes(vector<int>& parents) {
        int n = parents.size();
        N = n;
        vector<vector<int>> tree(n);

        for(int i=1; i<n; i++){

            tree[parents[i]].push_back(i);
        }

        dfs(0,tree);
        int cntOfMax = 0;

        for(long& s: allScores){
            if(s==maxScore) cntOfMax++;
        }
        return cntOfMax;
    }
};
```

