# EXPLANATION
We took **m** for max value, **c** for the count as answer, **n** for size of parents.
Created a vector of size **n** with pair **<int,int>** as child value and initialised its value to **{-1,-1}**.
Traversed through parents vector and added the child to the number if present.**(Created a binary tree path)**.
We did **sol(0,v,n-1)** because the start root is 0 and we need to remove one root every time so we did (n-1).
In **sol** function we traversed in DFS technique.
If there is no child we return 0.
We stored **l** -> left child value, **r** -> right child value.
Stored **lsum** -> no. of left root sum ,**rsum** -> no. of right root sum.
Took **s** -> no. of root sum except lsum and rsum (roots above it).
**ls** and **rs** for calculation of total roots as asked in question.
We used **max function** because of calculation (in some cases there is no child or no root above it so in order for calculation we need to multiply with 1).
Compared with **m** and did the operation as required.
At last returned the number of child roots along with it.
Finally returned **c**.
# SOLUTION
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long m=0;
    int c=0;
    int countHighestScoreNodes(vector<int>& parents) {
       int n=parents.size();
       vector<pair<int,int>> v(n,pair<int,int>({-1,-1}));
       for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
           int a=parents[i];
           if(v[a].first==-1)
                v[a].first=i;
            else
                v[a].second=i;
       }
       sol(0,v,n-1);
       return c;
    }
    int sol(int i,vector<pair<int,int>> &v,int n){
        if(i==-1)
            return 0;
        int l=v[i].first,r=v[i].second;
        int lsum=0,rsum=0;
        lsum=sol(l,v,n);
        rsum=sol(r,v,n);
        long long s=max(1,n-lsum-rsum);
        long long ls=max(1,lsum);
        long long rs=max(1,rsum);
        long long res=s*ls*rs;
        if(res==m)
            c++;
        else if(res>m)
            c=1;
        m=max(m,res);
        return (lsum+rsum+1);
    }
};
```

