solutions.content:
The key to this problem is recognizing that a node's score is the product of three terms:
1. Left Child Count
2. Right Child Count
3. Parent Node Count = (Total Node Count - 1 - leftChildCount - rightChildCount)

As you'll see below, in cases where Left/Right Child Count is 0, we multiply by 1 instead.

The prompt tells us that node 0 is the root. Therefore, if we perform a dfs on 0 then we can populate a leftNodeCount and rightNodeCount for each node along the way. As we dfs, we can keep track of our max and max count.

Comment key from below:
*1  Each term can return 0, but we don't want to multiply by 0. I add in ||| 1 so that (0 || 1) = 1 which won't affect the curScore.

# Code
```
/**
 * @param {number[]} parents
 * @return {number}
 */
var countHighestScoreNodes = function(parents) {
    const N = parents.length;
    // first we must create a graph of children from our parents array
    const graph = new Array(N).fill().map(() => []);
    for (let i = 1; i < N; i++) {
        graph[parents[i]].push(i);
    }

    let highestScore = 0;
    let highestScoreCount = 0;
    var traverse = function (node) {
        if (node === undefined) return 0;
        const children = graph[node]
        const leftChildCount = traverse(children[0]);
        const rightChildCount = traverse(children[1]);
        // -1 to account for the node we are removing
        const parentCount = N - leftChildCount - rightChildCount - 1;

        const curScore = (leftChildCount || 1) * (rightChildCount || 1) * (parentCount || 1); // *1

        // reset max score and max count when curScore > highestScore
        if (curScore > highestScore) {
            highestScore = curScore;
            highestScoreCount = 1;
        } 
        // increase max count when curScore === highestScore
        else if (curScore === highestScore) highestScoreCount++;

        return 1 + leftChildCount + rightChildCount
    }

    traverse(0);
    return highestScoreCount;
};
```

